{
  "recommendation": "Avoid enflurane and all volatile halogenated anesthetic agents. Use a non-triggering anesthetic technique (total intravenous anesthesia, TIVA). The RYR1 'No Result' should be addressed by repeat testing; in the interim, treat the patient as potentially MH-susceptible. Consider referral for definitive MH susceptibility testing via in vitro contracture test (IVCT/CHCT) if clinically feasible. Ensure dantrolene is immediately available in the operating room for any procedure requiring anesthesia.",
  "classification": "Strong",
  "implication": "The patient has an uncertain CACNA1S variant (uncertain susceptibility, i.e., a variant of unclear clinical significance) and no interpretable RYR1 result. Together, these findings do not exclude malignant hyperthermia (MH) susceptibility. CACNA1S encodes the alpha-1 subunit of the skeletal muscle dihydropyridine receptor (CaV1.1), which normally exerts negative allosteric regulation over the type 1 ryanodine receptor (RyR1). Functional studies (PMID 15201141, 22547813) demonstrate that CACNA1S variants such as R1086H and R174W disrupt this inhibitory coupling, sensitizing RyR1 to volatile anesthetic-triggered Ca2+ release — the primary pathophysiological mechanism of MH. The 'Uncertain Susceptibility' designation means a pathogenic effect cannot be excluded for the detected CACNA1S variant. Because RYR1 (the major MH locus, accounting for ~70% of MHS families) could not be evaluated, the patient's full genetic risk is indeterminate. Enflurane, as a volatile halogenated agent, is a recognized MH trigger. Given the potentially fatal consequences of an MH episode and the availability of equally effective non-triggering alternatives, the precautionary approach is warranted regardless of genotype certainty."
}

